### Functional Explanation
A 250MHz clock frequency corresponds to a clock period of $T = 1 / 250\text{ MHz} = 4.0\text{ ns}$. All logic plus routing delay must resolve within this 4.0ns window.

### Potential Issues
1. **Critical Path Delay**: A 32-bit standard adder (like `assign sum = a + b`) inferred as a ripple-carry adder might struggle to meet a 4.0ns timing budget on older or lower-speed-grade FPGAs. Modern FPGAs (like Xilinx 7-series or UltraScale) use dedicated carry chains (CARRY4/CARRY8 primitives) that can easily hit 250MHz for 32 bits, but routing delays to and from the adder could still cause violations.
2. **Setup and Hold Times**: The propagation delay of the adder ($T_{pd}$) plus the setup time of the destination register ($T_{setup}$) and routing delay ($T_{route}$) must be less than 4.0ns: $T_{cq} + T_{route1} + T_{pd} + T_{route2} + T_{setup} < 4.0\text{ ns}$.

### Fix
If timing fails at 250MHz, apply pipelining to cut the critical path:
```verilog
module pipelined_adder(input clk, input [31:0] a, b, output reg [32:0] sum);
  reg [31:0] a_reg, b_reg;
  always @(posedge clk) begin
    // Input pipeline registers
    a_reg <= a;
    b_reg <= b;
    // Output pipeline register (adder maps to dedicated DSP or carry chain)
    sum <= a_reg + b_reg;
  end
endmodule
```

