### Recommended Fix
```verilog
module pulse_sync_50_to_200 (
  input clk_50,  input rst_50,  input pulse_in,
  input clk_200, input rst_200, output pulse_out
);

  // 1. Source Domain (50MHz): Convert pulse to toggle
  reg toggle_reg;
  always @(posedge clk_50) begin
    if (rst_50) toggle_reg <= 1'b0;
    else if (pulse_in) toggle_reg <= ~toggle_reg;
  end

  // 2. Destination Domain (200MHz): 2-FF Synchronizer
  // The ASYNC_REG attribute prevents shift-register extraction and places FFs together.
  (* ASYNC_REG = "TRUE" *) reg sync1, sync2;
  always @(posedge clk_200) begin
    if (rst_200) {sync2, sync1} <= 2'b0;
    else {sync2, sync1} <= {sync1, toggle_reg};
  end

  // 3. Destination Domain: Edge detection (delay by 1 cycle)
  reg sync3;
  always @(posedge clk_200) begin
    if (rst_200) sync3 <= 1'b0;
    else sync3 <= sync2;
  end

  // Recreate the pulse
  assign pulse_out = sync2 ^ sync3;

endmodule
```

### Timing / Synthesis Considerations
Since we are passing data from 50MHz to 200MHz, the 200MHz domain samples 4 times faster than the 50MHz domain. Even a standard 2-FF synchronizer without the toggle logic *might* catch the pulse, but if the pulse width generated by the 50MHz domain is exactly one 50MHz cycle (20ns), the toggle synchronizer guarantees the event is captured and guarantees only exactly ONE `pulse_out` is produced for exactly one `clk_200` cycle (5ns). A raw 2-FF synchronizer would stretch the output pulse to 4 cycles.

