The Xilinx DSP48E2 slice features a pre-adder, a 27x18 two's complement multiplier, and a 48-bit accumulator. Achieving 400MHz requires engaging the internal DSP pipeline registers: `INMODE`, `A`, `B`, `M` (Multiplier), and `P` (Product).

### Potential Issues
Writing standard `a * b` without surrounding registers will force the multiplier to act combinationally, dropping Fmax to < 100MHz.

### Recommended Fix
```verilog
module dsp_27x18_pipe (
  input clk,
  input signed [26:0] a,
  input signed [17:0] b,
  output reg signed [44:0] p
);
  // Stage 1: Input registers (Maps to A_REG and B_REG)
  reg signed [26:0] a_reg;
  reg signed [17:0] b_reg;

  // Stage 2: Multiplier register (Maps to M_REG)
  reg signed [44:0] m_reg;

  always @(posedge clk) begin
    // Pipeline Stage 1
    a_reg <= a;
    b_reg <= b;

    // Pipeline Stage 2
    m_reg <= a_reg * b_reg;

    // Pipeline Stage 3 (Maps to P_REG)
    p <= m_reg;
  end
endmodule
```

### Timing / Synthesis Considerations
By inserting exactly 3 clock cycles of latency directly before, during, and after the arithmetic operation, the synthesis tool (Vivado) will perfectly absorb all registers into the `DSP48E2` primitive. This eliminates all fabric routing delays (since the signals never leave the silicon hard-macro), easily allowing operations up to 600+ MHz on UltraScale+.

